captions.text:
00:02
VET: Come on little one.

00:04
COMM: A dedicated vet makes a desperate attempt
to save a jaguar cubs life.

00:10
COMM: Just seconds after it's birth.

00:19
COMM: Female jaguar Xena underwent a caesarean

operation at the El Bosque Veterinary Hospital
in Madrid in February this year.

00:30
COMM: Found predominately in South America,

the jaguar is a near threatened species with
an estimated 15,000 left in the wild.

00:40
COMM: Vets at the hospital opted for a cesarean

after Xena had previously killed two cubs
after giving birth to them.

00:52
COMM: The surgery initially went well and

a young male was born. But vets feared the
worst when the cub appeared lifeless and wasn't
breathing.

01:06
COMM: A team of 12 vets, nurses and assistants

quickly set about trying to save the tiny
cub. In a frantic and tense 8 minutes, the

team attempted CPR and even mouth to mouth
resuscitation.

01:22
VET: Come on little one.

01:25
COMM: Eventually, a heart beat was found.

01:35
COMM: Unaware of his dramatic entry into the

world, the cub - affectionately named Ali
- was nursed back to health. He has now been

re-homed at a local zoo where he is being
hand raised by carers.

title: Cute Newborn Jaguar Cub Saved By Vets

26 de marzo de 2014
Lindo recién nacido Jaguar
Cub Guardado por los veterinarios

Boca a boca con un Jaguar


Un veterinario DEDICADO ayudó a salvar un jaguar muerto - dándole el beso 
de la vida. Estas fotografías conmovedoras muestran un equipo de 
veterinarios españoles realizar una cesárea y luego tener que resucitar el 
cachorro que resulta que no estaba respirando. El nacimiento dramática se 
desarrolló en el Hospital El Bosque Veterinaria en Madrid, España. El joven 
cachorro llamado Ali está siendo criado a mano, ya que no puede ser 
devuelto a su madre.﻿
